Web Spring Coffee

Technical details	
Submit file	./src/main/java/*.java, pom.xml or build.gradle, README.md, etc.
I want my Coffee on the Web, FASTER!
Objective
Enhance the coffee shop application to incorporate Spring MVC for web functionalities, Hibernate for database interactions, and WebSocket for real-time communication between customers and baristas.

Application Overview
This enhanced coffee shop application will allow customers to:

Place orders through a web interface.

Communicate with baristas in real-time using WebSocket.

View order status updates immediately as they happen.

Manage coffee orders and chat history stored in a database using Hibernate.

Requirements
1. Project Structure:
Create a Spring Boot project with the following packages:
controller
service
repository
model
config
websocket
factory
observer
strategy
decorator
singleton
command
adapter
facade
prototype
template
2. Implementations:
A. Spring MVC for Web Interface
Controller Layer: Create controllers to handle web requests for placing orders and viewing order statuses.

Thymeleaf Template Engine: Use Thymeleaf for rendering HTML views.

Example Controller


@Controller
public class CoffeeShopController {

    @GetMapping("/")
    public String home(Model model) {
        [...]
    }

    @PostMapping("/order")
    public String placeOrder(Order order) {
        [...]
    }

    @GetMapping("/orders")
    public String viewOrders(Model model) {
        [...]
    }
}
B. Hibernate for Database Interactions
Entity Classes: Define entity classes for Order, Coffee, and ChatMessage using Hibernate annotations.
Example Entity

import javax.persistence.*;

@Entity
public class Order {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    
    private String coffeeType;
    private String status;
}
Repository Layer: Use Spring Data JPA repositories to manage database operations.
Example Repository

import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.JpaRepository;

public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {
    List<Order> findByStatus(String status);
}
C. WebSocket for Real-Time Communication
WebSocket Configuration: Set up WebSocket configuration for handling chat and order notifications.
Example WebSocket Configuration


@Configuration
@EnableWebSocket
public class WebSocketConfig implements WebSocketConfigurer {
    @Override
    public void registerWebSocketHandlers(WebSocketHandlerRegistry registry) {
        registry.addHandler(new ChatWebSocketHandler(), "/chat").setAllowedOrigins("*");
    }
}
WebSocket Handler: Implement a handler to manage WebSocket messages.
Example WebSocket Handler

import org.springframework.web.socket.TextMessage;
import org.springframework.web.socket.WebSocketSession;
import org.springframework.web.socket.handler.TextWebSocketHandler;

public class ChatWebSocketHandler extends TextWebSocketHandler {
    @Override
    public void handleTextMessage(WebSocketSession session, TextMessage message) {
    }
}
3. Application Flow:
Customers access the web application to view coffee options and place orders.

Orders are processed and stored in the database using Hibernate.

Customers and baristas communicate in real-time through the WebSocket connection.

Customers receive immediate updates on their order status.

4. Database Configuration:
Configure Hibernate with Spring Boot in application.properties.
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/coffeeshop
spring.datasource.username=root
spring.datasource.password=yourpassword
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update
spring.jpa.show-sql=true
5. Security (Optional):
Implement basic security using Spring Security for authentication and authorization.

